sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1585321
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: glgCAB for polycistronic expression of glycogen synthesis genes in E.coli
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This composite part combines all 3 enzymes enzymes involved in glycogen synthesis. GlgC creates ADP-glucose from glucose-1-phosphate, GlgA elongates alpha-1,4-linked chains and GlgB catalyzes the formation of alpha-1,6-linked branches.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Sarah Lubjuhn, Laura Helleckes, Michael Osthege

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1585312
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This is the translational unit of GlgC. It creates ADP-glucose from glucose-1-phosphate for glycogen synthesis.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Michael Osthege, Sarah Lubjuhn, Laura Helleckes

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1585310
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This is the translational unit of GlgA (Glycogen synthase) for elongation of glycogen chains. Through autophosphorylation, GlgA is also the starting point of glycogen synthesis in bacteria.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Laura Helleckes, Michael Osthege, Sarah Lubjuhn

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1585311
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This is the translational unit of GlgB (glycogen branching enzyme) from E. coli. The enzyme catalyzes the formation of alpha-1,6-branches in glycogen synthesis.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Sarah Lubjuhn, Laura Helleckes, Michael Osthege

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0034
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Vinay S Mahajan, Voichita D. Marinescu, Brian Chow, Alexander D Wissner-Gross and Peter Carr IAP, 2003.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Varies from -6 to +1 region from original sequence to accomodate BioBricks suffix.

No secondary structures are formed in the given RBS region. Users should check for secondary structures induced in the RBS by upstream and downstream elements in the +50 to -50 region, as such structures will greatly affect the strength of the RBS. Contact info for this part: Brian Chow

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K118016
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This is the coding sequence of ''glgC'' (ADP-glucose pyrophosphorylase) from ''Escherichia coli'' JM109 with the substitution G336D. This mutation is known to cause increased activity of ADP-glucose pyrophosphorylase in the absence of the activator fructose 1,6-bisphosphate (FBP), high affinity for FBP and substrates lower affinity for the inhibitor AMP. (Leung ''et al'', 1986; Meyer ''et al.'', 1988)
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Andrew Hall
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: The mutation G336D was achieved by the substitution of A for G at position 1076 (codon GGC->GAC) by MABEL.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1585300
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Glycogen synthase GlgA from E. coli K12
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
The glycogen synthase synthesizes alpha-1,4-glucan chains using ADP-glucose.
The BioBrick was created from the genomic sequence of glgA in ''E. coli'' K12.
Six illegal restriction sites were removed to ensure full BioBrick compability.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Michael Osthege
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The BioBrick was created from the genomic sequence of glgA in ''E. coli'' K12.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: Six illegal restriction sites were removed to ensure full BioBrick compability. The native stop codon was replaced with TAATAA.
